            <!-- Educational content -->
            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the SOFA score?</h2>
              <p>
                The
                <strong
                  >Sequential Organ Failure Assessment (SOFA) score</strong
                >
                is a validated tool used in intensive care units (ICUs) to
                quantify the degree of organ dysfunction in critically ill
                patients. It was originally developed by the European Society of
                Intensive Care Medicine and is widely used in sepsis research
                and ICU outcome prediction.
              </p>
              <p>
                SOFA evaluates <strong>six organ systems</strong>, each scored
                from 0 (normal) to 4 (severe dysfunction):
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Respiratory – PaO₂/FiO₂ ratio (or SpO₂/FiO₂ surrogate)</li>
                <li>Coagulation – Platelet count</li>
                <li>Liver – Total bilirubin</li>
                <li>
                  Cardiovascular – Mean arterial pressure and vasopressor
                  requirements
                </li>
                <li>Central nervous system – Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS)</li>
                <li>Renal – Serum creatinine and/or urine output</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The <strong>total SOFA score</strong> is the sum of the six
                sub-scores, ranging from 0 to 24. Higher scores and increases
                over time are associated with higher mortality.
              </p>

              <h2>SOFA score components and thresholds</h2>

              <h3>1. Respiratory system – PaO₂/FiO₂ (mmHg)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>PaO₂/FiO₂ ratio</strong> (mmHg):</p>
                <p class="mb-2">
                  \[ \text{PaO₂/FiO₂} = \frac{\text{PaO₂ (mmHg)}}{\text{FiO₂ (as
                  a fraction)}} \] where FiO₂ (%) ÷ 100 = FiO₂ (fraction).
                </p>
                <table class="w-full text-xs border mt-2">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-left">
                        PaO₂/FiO₂ (mmHg)
                      </th>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">
                        Respiratory SOFA
                      </th>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-left">
                        Typical interpretation
                      </th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">&gt; 400</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">0</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">Normal oxygenation</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">&le; 400</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">1</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">Mild impairment</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">&le; 300</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">2</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">Moderate impairment</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">
                        &le; 200 (with respiratory support)
                      </td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">3</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">Severe impairment</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">
                        &le; 100 (with respiratory support)
                      </td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">4</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">Very severe impairment</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm">
                In this calculator, if you provide
                <strong>SpO₂/FiO₂</strong> instead of PaO₂/FiO₂, we use
                approximate cut-offs derived from published correlations. This
                is helpful when arterial blood gas is not available, but ABG
                remains the reference standard.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Coagulation – Platelet count</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <table class="w-full text-xs border">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-left">
                        Platelets (×10³/µL)
                      </th>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">
                        Coagulation SOFA
                      </th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">&ge; 150</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">0</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">&lt; 150</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">1</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">&lt; 100</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">2</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">&lt; 50</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">3</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">&lt; 20</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">4</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Liver – Total bilirubin</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>Unit conversion:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Bilirubin (mg/dL)} = \frac{\text{Bilirubin
                  (µmol/L)}}{17.1} \]
                </p>
                <table class="w-full text-xs border mt-2">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-left">
                        Bilirubin (mg/dL)
                      </th>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">Liver SOFA</th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">&lt; 1.2</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">0</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">1.2–1.9</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">1</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">2.0–5.9</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">2</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">6.0–11.9</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">3</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">&ge; 12.0</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">4</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Cardiovascular – MAP and vasopressors</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  The cardiovascular SOFA sub-score is based on the
                  <strong>worst category</strong> of hypotension and vasopressor
                  support:
                </p>
                <table class="w-full text-xs border mt-2">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-left">
                        Hemodynamic status
                      </th>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">
                        Cardiovascular SOFA
                      </th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">
                        MAP &ge; 70 mmHg, no vasopressors
                      </td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">0</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">MAP &lt; 70 mmHg</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">1</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">
                        Dopamine ≤ 5 µg/kg/min or any dobutamine
                      </td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">2</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">
                        Dopamine &gt; 5 and ≤ 15 µg/kg/min or norepinephrine ≤
                        0.1 µg/kg/min or epinephrine ≤ 0.1 µg/kg/min
                      </td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">3</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">
                        Dopamine &gt; 15 µg/kg/min or norepinephrine &gt; 0.1
                        µg/kg/min or epinephrine &gt; 0.1 µg/kg/min
                      </td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">4</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <h3>5. Central nervous system – Glasgow Coma Scale</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <table class="w-full text-xs border">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-left">GCS score</th>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">CNS SOFA</th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">15</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">0</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">13–14</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">1</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">10–12</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">2</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">6–9</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">3</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">&lt; 6</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">4</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <h3>6. Renal – Creatinine and urine output</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>Unit conversion:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Creatinine (mg/dL)} = \frac{\text{Creatinine
                  (µmol/L)}}{88.4} \]
                </p>
                <table class="w-full text-xs border mt-2">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-left">Renal criteria</th>
                      <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">Renal SOFA</th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">
                        Creatinine &lt; 1.2 mg/dL
                      </td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">0</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">Creatinine 1.2–1.9 mg/dL</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">1</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">Creatinine 2.0–3.4 mg/dL</td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">2</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">
                        Creatinine 3.5–4.9 mg/dL or urine &lt; 500 mL/day
                      </td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">3</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1">
                        Creatinine ≥ 5.0 mg/dL or urine &lt; 200 mL/day
                      </td>
                      <td class="border px-2 py-1 text-center">4</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <h2>How to interpret the SOFA score</h2>
              <p>
                The SOFA score is not a diagnosis but a
                <strong>measure of organ dysfunction</strong>. Both the absolute
                score and its change over time are important:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Baseline SOFA</strong> at ICU admission helps stratify
                  severity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>ΔSOFA (change over 24–48 hours)</strong> is strongly
                  associated with outcome; an increase of ≥ 2 points is
                  concerning.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Approximate mortality risk by SOFA score</h3>
              <p class="text-sm">
                Exact mortality depends on the population and setting, but a
                commonly cited pattern is:
              </p>
              <table class="w-full text-xs border">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-left">Total SOFA score</th>
                    <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-left">Risk category</th>
                    <th class="border px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Approximate in-hospital mortality
                    </th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">0–6</td>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">Low</td>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">&lt; 10–15%</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">7–9</td>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">Moderate</td>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">15–30%</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">10–12</td>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">High</td>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">30–50%</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">≥ 13</td>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">Very high</td>
                    <td class="border px-2 py-1">&gt; 50%</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2">
                These ranges are approximate and synthesized from multiple
                studies; they are provided for educational purposes only and
                should not replace local outcome data or clinical judgment.
              </p>

              <h2>SOFA vs qSOFA</h2>
              <p>
                The <strong>qSOFA (quick SOFA)</strong> score is a simplified
                bedside tool that uses only three variables (altered mentation,
                respiratory rate ≥ 22/min, systolic blood pressure ≤ 100 mmHg)
                to identify patients at risk of poor outcomes outside the ICU.
                It does <em>not</em> replace the full SOFA score but can be used
                as a screening tool.
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator focuses on the <strong>full SOFA score</strong>,
                which requires laboratory data and is more accurate for ICU risk
                stratification and sepsis-related organ dysfunction assessment.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and clinical caveats</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  SOFA was developed for ICU populations; performance may differ
                  in other settings.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Scores can be affected by chronic organ dysfunction (e.g.,
                  chronic liver disease, CKD); consider baseline values.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Vasopressor dosing and availability vary by institution; map
                  your local practice to the original categories.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Always interpret SOFA in the context of the full clinical
                  picture, not in isolation.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Can I calculate SOFA without arterial blood gas?</h3>
              <p>
                When PaO₂ is not available, some clinicians use
                <strong>SpO₂/FiO₂</strong> as a surrogate for PaO₂/FiO₂. This is
                less precise but may be acceptable for trend monitoring.
                Whenever possible, obtain arterial blood gas for accurate
                respiratory assessment.
              </p>

              <h3>How often should I recalculate the SOFA score?</h3>
              <p>
                In many ICUs, SOFA is calculated at admission and then
                <strong>daily</strong>, or more frequently in unstable patients.
                The change in SOFA over the first 24–48 hours is particularly
                informative.
              </p>

              <h3>Is a SOFA increase of 2 points always sepsis?</h3>
              <p>
                In the Sepsis-3 framework, sepsis is defined as suspected or
                confirmed infection plus an acute increase in SOFA of ≥ 2
                points. However, SOFA can also increase due to non-infectious
                causes (e.g., trauma, pancreatitis). Clinical context is
                essential.
              </p>

              <h2>References</h2>
              <ul class="text-sm">
                <li>
